ls - List files
Example: ls -l (show details)

cd - Change directory
Example: cd ~/Documents

mkdir - Create folder
Example: mkdir new_project

rm - Delete files
Example: rm old_file.txt

What pwd Does:
Prints the full path of your current directory (folder) in the terminal.


- man → Shows help/manual for a command  
  Example: `man ls`

- q → Quit a manual page or viewer  
  Example: Press `q` inside `man`


View contents of a file

cat file.txt

Create a new file

cat > newfile.txt


(Type your text, then press Ctrl + D to save & exit.)

Append text to an existing file

cat >> file.txt

Combine (concatenate) multiple files

cat file1.txt file2.txt > merged.txt

file

Tells the type of a file (text, image, binary, etc).

Example:

file notes.txt


Output:

notes.txt: ASCII text

touch

Creates an empty file or updates the timestamp of a file.

Example:

touch hello.txt


→ Creates an empty file hello.txt.
